{"batch":"test_strategy","batch_index":17,"assessments":{"test_strategy":24.0},"dimension_notes":{"test_strategy":{"evidence":["The repository has no test files at all: a search for `pytest`, `unittest`, `assert`, `snapshot`, `golden`, and `hypothesis` only finds text inside `AGENTS.md`, so the main data-processing scripts are unvalidated by any automated test suite.","Core possession and foul-labeling logic lives in production functions such as `parse_possessions` in `step2_build_possessions.py`, `build_table` in `build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py`, and `build_def_foul_context` in `categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py`, but none of those paths are exercised by fixtures covering edge cases like missing clock values, non-two-team payloads, same-clock events, or foul subtype filtering.","The season aggregators in `calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py` and `calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py` combine network fetch, retry policy, concurrency, parsing, and metric aggregation in one path, yet there are no integration tests with stubbed API payloads to verify that a season summary stays correct under partial failures or malformed games.","The scripts are tightly coupled to live NBA endpoints and CSV files (`requests.get` / `session.get`, `pd.read_csv`, `to_csv`, and `main()` entry points), so the only apparent verification mode is manual script execution against external state, which is a fragile strategy for regression detection."],"impact_scope":"codebase","fix_scope":"architectural_change","confidence":"high"}},"issues":[{"dimension":"test_strategy","identifier":"no_automated_coverage_for_core_metrics","summary":"The repo has no automated tests for the core possession and WMI calculations.","related_files":["step2_build_possessions.py","build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py","categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py","calculate_wmi_rawgame_okc_mil.py"],"evidence":["`parse_possessions` (`step2_build_possessions.py`) contains the possession segmentation logic, including same-clock ordering and defensive foul counting, but there is no corresponding test file in the repository.","`build_table` (`build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py`) derives `L_t`, `F_t`, `N_t`, and `M_t`, and `calculate_wmi_rawgame` (`calculate_wmi_rawgame_okc_mil.py`) turns those into the headline metric, yet no automated assertions verify these formulas on a known play-by-play fixture.","A repo-wide search for common Python test patterns finds no test modules at all, so changes to these critical paths would only be caught by manual reruns."],"suggestion":"Add a real test suite with fixture-based unit tests for possession grouping, defensive foul classification, score-side inference, and WMI math. Start with small in-memory play-by-play DataFrames that assert exact `L_t/F_t/N_t/M_t` outputs and final WMI values.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"codebase","fix_scope":"architectural_change","root_cause_cluster":"missing_automated_test_harness"},{"dimension":"test_strategy","identifier":"no_integration_tests_for_network_to_summary_pipeline","summary":"Season-level pipelines have no integration coverage despite spanning fetch, retry, parsing, and aggregation.","related_files":["calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py","calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py"],"evidence":["`compute_season` in `calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py` fans out concurrent requests, classifies results as ok/missing/error, and then computes pooled WMI from aggregated counters, but there is no test that feeds controlled game payloads through that full flow.","`main` in `calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py` retries failed game IDs and then derives a one-row summary from concatenated possession tables; without an integration-style test, regressions in retry handling or aggregation would silently change reported season outputs.","Both files depend on live CDN responses during execution, so correctness currently depends on external availability instead of deterministic fixtures."],"suggestion":"Introduce integration tests that monkeypatch the request layer or inject a fake session, then run a small multi-game season through the full pipeline and assert the resulting summary counters and WMI fields.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","root_cause_cluster":"missing_automated_test_harness"},{"dimension":"test_strategy","identifier":"logic_is_hard_to_test_due_to_io_coupling","summary":"Business logic is entangled with live HTTP and file I/O, which blocks isolated testing.","related_files":["build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py","categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py","calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py"],"evidence":["`build_table` fetches the live play-by-play JSON itself before doing all downstream derivation, instead of accepting already-loaded actions or a DataFrame as its primary interface.","`build_def_foul_context` likewise performs the network call internally, making the classification logic depend on an external API even when a test only wants to validate foul-context rules.","`build_possession_table_for_game` in `calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py` bundles HTTP fetch, parsing, and possession metric derivation in one function, so tests cannot target the metric logic without also faking transport behavior."],"suggestion":"Split each script into pure transformation functions that accept actions/DataFrames and thin I/O wrappers that fetch or write files. Then test the pure functions directly and cover the wrappers with a small number of mocked integration tests.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"codebase","fix_scope":"architectural_change","root_cause_cluster":"missing_automated_test_harness"},{"dimension":"test_strategy","identifier":"manual_script_runs_are_the_only_regression_check","summary":"The current verification approach appears to be manual reruns against moving external data.","related_files":["step2_build_possessions.py","build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py","categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py","calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py","calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py"],"evidence":["Each file is structured as a top-level script with hard-coded IDs or output paths and a `main()` block, but there are no stable fixture files or assertions that lock expected outputs.","The season scripts classify network failures broadly and keep going, which means two runs can differ because of transient API behavior without any automated signal that a behavioral regression happened.","Because the only visible outputs are printed summaries and CSV writes, a developer changing possession logic has no fast feedback loop beyond rerunning scripts and eyeballing results."],"suggestion":"Create deterministic fixture payloads and expected result snapshots at the data-frame level, then wire them into automated tests so script reruns are not the primary safety net. Keep manual script execution only as an exploratory check.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"codebase","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","root_cause_cluster":"missing_automated_test_harness"}],"retrospective":{"root_causes":["The project is organized as standalone analysis scripts rather than a testable package, so core transformations never got a reusable test harness.","Data-fetching, parsing, and metric computation are mixed together, which raises the cost of writing even basic deterministic tests."],"likely_symptoms":["no_automated_coverage_for_core_metrics","no_integration_tests_for_network_to_summary_pipeline","logic_is_hard_to_test_due_to_io_coupling","manual_script_runs_are_the_only_regression_check"],"possible_false_positives":[]}}
